{"name":"Mathlib.Analysis.NormedSpace.RieszLemma","instances":[],"imports":["Init","Mathlib.Analysis.NormedSpace.Basic","Mathlib.Analysis.Seminorm","Mathlib.Topology.MetricSpace.HausdorffDistance"],"declarations":[{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Mathlib/Analysis/NormedSpace/RieszLemma.lean#L113-L119","name":"Metric.closedBall_infDist_compl_subset_closure","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Mathlib/Analysis/NormedSpace/RieszLemma.html#Metric.closedBall_infDist_compl_subset_closure","doc":""},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Mathlib/Analysis/NormedSpace/RieszLemma.lean#L88-L110","name":"riesz_lemma_of_norm_lt","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Mathlib/Analysis/NormedSpace/RieszLemma.html#riesz_lemma_of_norm_lt","doc":"A version of Riesz lemma: given a strict closed subspace `F`, one may find an element of norm `≤ R`\nwhich is at distance at least `1` of every element of `F`. Here, `R` is any given constant\nstrictly larger than the norm of an element of norm `> 1`. For a version without an `R`, see\n`riesz_lemma`.\n\nSince we are considering a general nontrivially normed field, there may be a gap in possible norms\n(for instance no element of norm in `(1,2)`). Hence, we can not allow `R` arbitrarily close to `1`,\nand require `R > ‖c‖` for some `c : 𝕜` with norm `> 1`.\n"},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Mathlib/Analysis/NormedSpace/RieszLemma.lean#L46-L75","name":"riesz_lemma","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Mathlib/Analysis/NormedSpace/RieszLemma.html#riesz_lemma","doc":"Riesz's lemma, which usually states that it is possible to find a\nvector with norm 1 whose distance to a closed proper subspace is\narbitrarily close to 1. The statement here is in terms of multiples of\nnorms, since in general the existence of an element of norm exactly 1\nis not guaranteed. For a variant giving an element with norm in `[1, R]`, see\n`riesz_lemma_of_norm_lt`. "}]}